\section{GENERAL}

%********************************************************************

\subsection{Scope}

This document gives user oriented description of a text formatting
facility which allows the use of \LaTeX\ to prepare documents
containing Z, HOL and similar formal material.  The facilities are
similar in spirit to those described in \cite{DS/FMU/infra/006}, for
preparing such documents using {\tt ptroff}, but offer several
additional features.

This document describes the version of the system which works with
\TeX\ version~3.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{Introduction}

Some utility programs and supporting files have been produced to assist
in the handling of literate scripts, \ie, files containing a mixture of
formal material (\eg, HOL, Standard~ML code, or Z) and narrative text.
The utilities support the extraction of formal material for processing
(\eg, by the Standard~ML compiler) or for typesetting.  The typesetting
aspects are oriented towards \LaTeX, but some are suitable for use with
other typesetting systems, such as {\tt ptroff.}

For typesetting the package contains of a \LaTeX\ style file (\ie, a
macro suite) named {\tt hol.sty}; a preprocessor program, {\tt
doc2tex}; and a font {\tt newzfont.}  There are two shell scripts {\tt
doc4tex} and {\tt tex4dvi} which are the recommended means of calling
{\tt doc2tex} and running \LaTeX\ in normal use.

The preprocessor allows the user to prepare a \LaTeX\
file using the extended character set described in
\cite{DS/FMU/infra/006}, this character set is often
called the ``pretty character set.''  With this character
set the formal material appears on the screen much
as it does in the printed document, while the format of
the file is compatible with the HOL system, {\it via}
the interfaces described in \cite{DS/FMU/infra/006}.

This document describes the typesetting facilities, largely by
example.  We assume some familiarity with \LaTeX, which is described in
\cite{lamport86} and with the HOL infrastructure for supporting Z-like
constructs described in~\cite{DS/FMU/infra/002}.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{Note On Compatibility}

Literate scripts which contain formal text for processing with
the Cambridge HOL system may be typeset with \LaTeX\ using
{\tt doc4tex} and {\tt tex4dvi}, provided the pretty characters
`\Sh{\Startinfixaxdes}', `$\lceil$', `$\lfloor$',
`\Sh{\Topleft}', `\Sh{\Topright}', `\Sh{\Bottomleft}' and
`\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' \etc,
are used to delimit the formal material rather than troff macros.
The facilities described in \cite{DS/FMU/infra/006} may be used to
extract the formal material for processing by Cambridge HOL.
Theory listings may be included in literate scripts provided they
are first processed with {\tt doc2tex} using the {\tt -i} option.

