\section{FILE FORMATS}

Various files are read or written by the programs in the package.
Three letter suffixes are used in file names to distinguish the various
file formats involved.  These are described in table
\ref{FileSuffixes}.  Note that the master format for a literate script
is the {\tt .doc} format; the other formats are derived from this by
running programs which, in general, lose some information.

\begin{table}[h]

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{||l|p{5.5in}||} \hline
Suffix & Description \\ \hline \hline
{\tt .doc} & This is the usual format in which literate scripts
are held under SCCS control and in which they are edited.\\ \hline
{\tt .dvi} & This is the {\tt tex4dvi} output file (more precisely, it
is the \TeX\ or \LaTeX\ output file) which may be viewed with a screen
previewer, or printed.  \\ \hline
{\tt .idx} & This contains the raw index entries generated by running
\LaTeX\ on a file containing the command \verb"\makeindex". \\ \hline
{\tt .sid} & This is a sorted index file generated by {\tt tex4dvi}.
It is read by the \verb"\printindex" command described
in section~\ref{MakingAnIndex}. \\ \hline
{\tt .tex} & This is a \LaTeX\ input file. It is created
from a {\tt .doc} file using the utilities {\tt screen}
and {\tt doc2tex}. \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\caption{File Suffixes} \label{FileSuffixes}

\end{table}

There are several other file suffices that are used by \TeX\ and
\LaTeX\  for various purposes.  They are derived from the {\tt .tex}
file and are documented in the \TeX\ and \LaTeX\ books,~\cite{knuth84}
and~\cite{lamport86}.

