\section{FORMATTING DOCUMENTS}

%********************************************************************

\subsection{Getting Started}

To use the package you prepare a file, say {\tt myfile.doc}, using an
editor which supports an appropriate pretty font. The font {\tt
newzfont} is recommended.

The form of the file is essentially that of a
\LaTeX\ file except that you can use pretty
(\ie, non-ASCII) characters to type Z or HOL constructs.
A list of most of these characters is given in
section~\ref{ListOfPrettyCharacters} below.  The remaining pretty
characters are used for bracketing formal text for printing and other
processing, these characters are discussed elsewhere in this document.

The first \LaTeX\ command in the document (normally this is the
\verb"\documentstyle" command) should be preceded with a line
containing just the characters ``\verb"=TEX"''.  Any lines before this
are simply ignored.  The significance of this line will be made clear
in section~\ref{AboutScreen} where the {\tt screen} program and
the {\tt screenfile} are discussed.  For the moment, be aware that
any line whose first character is an equals sign ``{\tt=}'' indicates
the type of processing for the lines that follow.

The \verb"\documentstyle" command line that you use should include the
option {\tt hol}. \eg, this document starts with:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
	=TEX
\documentstyle[TQ,hol,11pt]{article}
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

to get the options {\tt TQ} (which gives our house style which is used
at an eleven point size) and {\tt hol}.

To process the file and produce a {\tt .dvi} file
you run the preprocessor then run \LaTeX\ as follows:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
doc4tex myfile
tex4dvi myfile
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

The above recipe assumes that you have put the directory containing the
programs on your search path --- all subsequent mentions of programs
will assume that the search path is set up correctly.  If your
document does not include a request to make an index as described in
\ref{MakingAnIndex} below, {\tt tex4dvi} will report on the fact that
the file {\tt myfile.idx} does not exist or cannot be read. This
message may be ignored if you do not wish your document to have an
index.  

The basic job of the preprocessor, {\tt doc2tex} is to translate each
non-ASCII character into \LaTeX\ macro calls which
typeset that character. Some non-ASCII characters
control the way in which it does this,
as we shall see.

Because of the way \LaTeX\ works when producing the self-referential
aspects of a document (\eg, table of contents, page and section
references, \etc) the program {\tt tex4dvi} will need to be run up to
four times.  If bibliographies use \BibTeX{} then the program {\tt
bibtex} should be run between the first and second execution of {\tt
tex4dvi}.

