\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\caption{\LaTeX\ Environments} \label{LaTeXEnvironments}
\end{table}

The environments marked with an asterisk (*) take
a parameter giving the name of the schema, the
parameters of the generic constant or the title
for the formal text.
These should be typed immediately after the `\Sh{\Topleft}'
character followed by optional padding (see below).
(Programs such as {\tt doc2sml, doc4sml} and
{\tt prettyhol} which process such
material may enforce extra rules. \Eg, the HOL
schema header must be terminated by a `\Sh{\Topright}'
character.)  The parameter to the {\tt FT} environment
is optional, its value, if present, is used to label
the printed output.

The {\tt FRule} has no pretty characters to introduce it, instead the
text given in the `Opening Bracket' column of
table~\ref{LaTeXEnvironments} should be written on a line on its own,
similarly for the `Closing Bracket' text.  Section~\ref{AboutFRules}
describes the {\tt FRule} environment in detail.

The shape of the bracketing characters has been chosen
so that you can use them, together with the pretty
characters `\Sh{\Vbar}', `\Sh{\Hbar}', `\Sh{\Bottomright}',
`\Sh{\Topright}', `\Sh{\ParallelLines}' and `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}',
to draw boxes which look on the screen like
the printed form.
The characters `\Sh{\Vbar}', `\Sh{\Hbar}', `\Sh{\Bottomright}',
`\Sh{\Topright}' and `\Sh{\ParallelLines}' are
merely padding and have no effect on the form of
the printed document, although other programs such as
{\tt prettyhol} may use them.  Within one of the three
sorts of HOL box, `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' causes the bar between the
signature and predicate parts of
the box to be printed. Only padding characters should
appear in the line after the `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}'.
(`\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' corresponds to a \LaTeX\ macro \verb"\crossbar".)

\label{LinesOfInput}
Within any of the above environments, text is typeset
with each ``line of input'' corresponding to a line in the
printed document.
Here if one of the bracketing character pairs listed
above encloses the text then the phrase ``line of input'' actually means
line of input; if you are
using \verb"\begin{...}" and \verb"\end{...}"
to delimit the environments, then  a ``line of input''
must have its beginning and end marked with
\verb"\+" and \verb"\\" respectively.

Tab and space characters may be used to control the layout within each
line of input.  All space characters give a small amount of space in
the printed output.  Tab characters are used to give type-writer style
tabbing, see section~\ref{AboutTabs} for more details.

