\subsection{Formatting Rules} \label{AboutFRules}

Rule structures have three main parts, conventionally the name, the
assumptions, and the conclusions.  They are displayed thus:

=RULE			RULE
name
…
assumptions
…
conclusions
=TEX			END RULE

Each of the three parts may have multiple lines.  The name part is
always aligned centrally with the horizontal line.  There may be one or
two horizontal lines.  Additionally, each structure may be labelled,
the word `Rule' labels the above display.

Similar layouts are used for conversions, tactics and theorems.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{Examples}

The {\em Modus Ponens\/} rule and the {\em induction
tactic\/} may be displayed as follows.

=RULE			RULE
›‚MP·
…
›ˆ∞ Ö t∞ ä t¨ ; ˆ¨ Ö t∞
…
›ˆ∞ ° ˆ¨ Ö t¨
=TEX			END RULE

=TACTIC			TACTIC
‚INDUCT_TAC·
…
É n é t[n]
…
t[0] ; {t[n]}t[SUC   n]
=TEX			END TACTIC

\parbox[t]{0.4\textwidth}{They are typed in the source text\\
approximately like this:}\kern0.1\textwidth
{\tt
\begin{tabular}[t]{l}
 =RULE\\
\Sh{\Vbar}\Startindex MP\Endindex\\
\Sh{\Bigturnstile}\Sh{\Hbar}\Sh{\Hbar}\Sh{\Hbar}\\
\Sh{\Vbar}ˆ∞ Ö t∞ ä t¨ ; ˆ¨ Ö t∞\\
\Sh{\Bigturnstile}\Sh{\Hbar}\Sh{\Hbar}\Sh{\Hbar}\\
\Sh{\Vbar}ˆ∞ ° ˆ¨ Ö t¨\\
 =TEX\\[2ex]
 =TACTIC\\
\Startindex INDUCT\_TAC\Endindex\\
\Sh{\Bigturnstile}\\
É n é t[n]\\
\Sh{\Bigturnstile}\\
t[0] ; {t[n]}t[SUC   n]\\
 =TEX
\end{tabular}}

Significant points shown above are as follows.

\begin{itemize}

\item The name, assumptions and conclusions are given in that order and
	are separated by the large turnstile `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' character,
	which should occur on a line on its own.

\item The use of the vertical `\Sh{\Vbar}' and horizontal `\Sh{\Hbar}' bars to
	make the source text more readable.

\item The type of rule box is indicated by the name after the equals
	`=' at the start of each rule, \ie, the \verb|=RULE| and
	\verb|=TACTIC| above.

\item The line \verb|=TEX| completes each rule.

\end{itemize}

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{\LaTeX\ Environment For Rules}
\label{LatexPrimScreenAddn}

The rule environments are implemented with the \LaTeX\ environment 
{\tt Frule}.  It takes two parameters.  First, a single digit, either~1
or~2, indicating the number of horizontal lines wanted.  Second the
label for the rule environment, or an empty parameter if no label is
wanted.

Using the {\tt Frule} environment is directly analogous to using
the~\ref{NumParts} components shown below.  The first component becomes
a call of \verb|\begin{Frule}{}{}|, the last a call of
\verb|\end{Frule}|, and the large turnstiles `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' are
calls of \verb|\crossbar|.

Within the name, assumptions and conclusions the lines of input must be
formatted according to the rules given in section~\ref{LinesOfInput},
this is most conveniently done by piping the text through the command
`{\tt doc2tex~-i}'.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{Format of Rule Environments}

A rule environment contains the following~\ref{NumParts} parts,
in the stated order.

\begin{enumerate}

\item A line containing the rule type at its start, types are given in
	section~\ref{TypesOfRule} below.

\item The name part.

\item A large turnstile `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' character with optional
	horizontal bars `\Sh{\Hbar}' on a line on their own.

\item The assumptions part.

\item Another large turnstile `\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' character with
	optional horizontal bars `\Sh{\Hbar}' on a line on their own.

\item The conclusions part.

\item \label{NumParts} Start another screening section, normally a line
	containing just the text {\tt =TEX}.

\end{enumerate}

Each of the name, assumptions and conclusions may comprise of several
lines, each of which may start with the optional vertical `\Sh{\Vbar}'
bar, if desired.  Lines in the assumptions and conclusions are
individually centered above or below the horizontal lines.  The name
part is left justified.  An example:

=CONVERSION
Name line 1
2
Third name line
…
Assumptions line 1
2
Third assumptions line
and the forth
…
First conclusions line
second
3
4, 4, 4, 4
fifth
=TEX

\parbox[t]{0.4\textwidth}{The source text
for this example is:}\kern0.1\textwidth
{\tt
\begin{tabular}[t]{l}
 =CONVERSION\\
Name line 1\\
2\\
Third name line\\
\Bigturnstile\\
Assumptions line 1\\
2\\
Third assumptions line\\
and the forth\\
\Bigturnstile\\
First conclusions line\\
second\\
3\\
4, 4, 4, 4\\
fifth\\
 =TEX
\end{tabular}}

Rule environments that contain only one large turnstile
`\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' character are assumed to contain just the name and
conclusion parts, those with no large turnstiles just the name part.
Any third or subsequent turnstile is ignored, any text that follows
them is treated as further lines of the conclusions.

Any rule environment with fewer, or greater, than two large turnstiles
`\Sh{\Bigturnstile}' characters will cause a warning message to be
written to the terminal and to the log file for the \LaTeX\ run.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsubsection{Types of Rule} \label{TypesOfRule}

A small number of types of rule are provided, each indicated by the
name following the equals `=' at the start of each line.  Some types
have one horizontal line, and some two.  Types supported at present
are:  {\tt =CONVERSION, =RULE} and {\tt =THEOREM} with one horizontal
line; and, {\tt =TACTIC} with two horizontal lines.  All of these types
are illustrated within this document.

Other types of rule may easily be added by updating the {\tt
screenfile} with lines similar to those shown below.  (The {\tt
screenfile} is used by the {\tt screen} program, see
section~\ref{AboutScreen}.)

The {\tt screenfile} entries for the four types of rule listed in this
section are as follows.

{\hfuzz 4.6pt
\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
RULE tex echo \\begin{Frule}1{Rule}; doc2tex -i ; echo \\end{Frule}
CONVERSION tex echo \\begin{Frule}1{Conversion}; doc2tex -i ; echo \\end{Frule}
THEOREM tex echo \\begin{Frule}1{Theorem}; doc2tex -i ; echo \\end{Frule}
TACTIC tex echo \\begin{Frule}2{Tactic}; doc2tex -i ; echo \\end{Frule}
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}
}

