\section{SUPPORTING PROGRAMS AND FILES}

The idiom for typesetting the literate script, {\tt myfile.doc} is:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
doc4tex myfile
tex4dvi myfile
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

This generates the file {\tt myfile.dvi} containing the \LaTeX\ output
for printing with {\tt pstex} or displaying with {\tt dvipage}.

The reason for having separate commands, {\tt doc4tex} and {\tt
tex4dvi}, is that one usually needs to run \LaTeX\ several times (\ie,
using {\tt tex4dvi} several times) to ensure that contents lists,
references and the like are all in step.

{\tt doc4tex}, {\tt tex4dvi} and the supporting utilities and files
are described in the following subsections.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt doc4tex\index{doc4tex}}}

This shell script takes a single command line option
which is the stem part of the name of a {\tt .tex}
file which is to be made from a {\tt .doc} file.
It uses {\tt sed}, {\tt screen} and {\tt doc2tex}
to do the transformation. The Standard~ML or HOL fragments in
the {\tt .doc} file may therefore be delimited either
using the {\tt screen} conventions (`{\tt =SML}', \etc)
or using the special characters (`\Sh{\StartML}', \etc).
The advantage of the combined approach is the ability
to control the inclusion, \eg, of diagnostic code
using the steering file, {\tt screenfile}, which
controls {\tt screen}.
If no steering file is present in the current
directory a default steering file suitable for most typical literate
scripts is used.

Note that using `\Sh{\StartML}' is normally preferred to using
`{\tt=SML}' for Standard~ML text.  The former allows are clear
distinction to be seen between the Standard~ML text and the embedded
HOL by printing them in different fonts.  The Standard~ML is printed
in an upright font.  An italic font is used for text surrounded by
either double quote characters `{\tt"}', as shown in
section~\ref{HOLExamples}, or by Strachey brackets `\Sh{ª}' and
`\Sh{º}'.  With `{\tt =SML}' all the text is displayed italic.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt tex4dvi\index{tex4dvi}}}

This shell script takes a single command line option which is the stem
part of the name of a {\tt .dvi} to be made from a {\tt .tex} file. It
runs \LaTeX\ once to generate the {\tt .dvi} file. If the \LaTeX\ run
has generated a {\tt .idx} file, this is sorted to produce a {\tt .sid}
file, otherwise an empty {\tt .sid} file is generated.  The {\tt .sid}
file is read by the \verb"\printindex" command.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt doc2tex\index{doc2tex}}}

This program is a filter which translates the {\tt .doc} format into
the {\tt .tex} format suitable for input to \LaTeX.  Most users will
wish to use {\tt doc4tex} rather than using {\tt doc2tex} directly.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt findfile\index{findfile}}}

This program allows shell scripts to be written without including
full path-names for steering files \etc \ It takes as command line
arguments a file name followed by a list of search paths in a
similar format to the shell's {\tt PATH} variable, \ie, a colon-separated
list of directory or file names, where a file name is taken to identify
the directory in which the file is contained. The C-shell's tilde
convention may be used in the names in the paths.
An example in a shell script might be:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
sed -f `findfile sedscript` $PATH $0`
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

Here the file {\tt sedscript} is sought for first in the directories
in the users {\tt PATH} shell variable and then in the directory
identified by the name with which this script was invoked.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt screen}\index{screen} --- A General Literate Script Utility}
\label{AboutScreen}

The program {\tt screen} implements a general literate script
mechanism. It is used to implement the specific mechanisms for scripts
containing \LaTeX\ and Standard~ML.  Its description is a little more
complex than that of the other utilities. We follow the style of the
UNIX manual pages:

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{SYNOPSIS}

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
screen [-v] [-f steering_file] view
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{DESCRIPTION}

This program is a filter which enables a single text file
to be used to hold data for processing by a range of different
programs. The view argument is used to indicate which program screen is
preparing the output for. (The idea is similar to Knuth's Web
system).

Directive lines are used to indicate that portions of the file belong
to particular `categories', where a category is just a tag.  A steering
file relates categories to `views' which are also just tags.

If no {\tt -f} option is given the steering file is assumed to be called
`{\tt screenfile}'. If the name does not begin with a `{\tt /}' and does
not identify a file in the current directory the program looks for
the steering file in the directories named in the environment variable
$PATH$. A steering file suitable for handling most literate scripts
using pretty characters is included in the directory in which {\tt screen}
is installed and will be found by this search algorithm if a special
steering file has not been prepared.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Steering File Format}

The steering file contains lines of the following forms:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
<category> <view> <filter>
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

This indicates that lines of category \verb/<category>/ are to be piped
through the command \verb/<filter>/ when screening to get view
\verb/<view>/. \ If no such line is present for a given category and
view then lines of that category are suppressed under that view.  The
\verb/<filter>/ may be omitted which is equivalent to using cat (but
faster). (The pipes are set up using popen(3S). Thus the
\verb/<filter>/ is interpreted by the Bourne shell sh(1)).  (A line of
this form may in fact be spread over several lines in the screenfile by
escaping the new line characters with backslash characters).

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
#<any text>
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

Lines of this form are ignored (as in fact are blank lines).

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Standard Input Format}

The directive lines in the standard input take the form:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
	=<category>
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

This indicates that the lines after the directive up to the next
directive or the end of the file are of category \verb/<category>/.
The `\verb/=/' must be the first character on the line. Text on a directive
line after the \verb/<category>/ is ignored
as is any text preceding the first directive.

Lines not starting with an `\verb/=/' character are processed according
to the category of the immediately preceding directive line.  Any lines
before the first directive line are ignored.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{EXAMPLE}

One might hold a program containing Fortran and C together
with its documentation using the following steering file:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
FORTRAN nroff ( echo .nf ; cat; echo .fi)
C nroff (echo .nf; cat; echo .fi)
C cc
FORTRAN f77
TEXT nroff
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

so that the code bits are included surrounded by \verb/.nf/ and \verb/.fi/
when the file is viewed to make a document and the relevant
languages only are presented when the file is viewed for compilation.

In the above example the input for screen might look like:

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
	=TEXT
	This program ...
	=FORTRAN
	        SUBROUTINE ...
	=C
	        main() ...
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

A file inclusion facility might be implemented as an extension
of the above example with a screenfile line of the form

\begin{quote}
\begin{verbatim}
INCLUDE nroff cat `cat` | screen nroff
\end{verbatim}
\end{quote}

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{OPTIONS}

\verb/-v/ causes copious tracing on the standard error channel.

%--------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{LIMITS}

No more than 40 categories per view.
Input lines must be less than 1024 bytes long.

%********************************************************************

\subsection{{\tt screenfile}\index{screenfile} --- Steering file for {\tt screen}}

The standard {\tt screenfile} contains entries for all the \LaTeX\
environments described in this document.  If additional features are
required for a particular file then a copy of the file can be made,
and extended, in directory holding the document needing these
additional features..

